SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT THIS SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT (this “Agreement”), is entered into as of _____________________, 2012 (the “Effective Date”), by and between Gray County Wind Energy, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Gray County Wind”) and Ensign Wind, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Ensign Wind”). Gray County Wind and Ensign Wind may be referred to herein individually as a “Party” and collectively as the “Parties.” RECITALS WHEREAS, Gray County Wind owns and/or operates a 112 MW wind-powered electric generating facility located in Gray County, Kansas (the “Gray County Wind Project”); WHEREAS, Ensign Wind is owns and operates an approximately 99 MW wind-powered electric generating facility located near the Gray County Project, in Gray and Meade Counties, Kansas (the “Ensign Wind Project”); WHEREAS, Gray County Wind is party to that certain Interconnection Agreement dated July 16, 2001 by and among itself and Mid-Kansas Electric Company, LLC (“MKEC”), as successor in interest to Utilicorp United Inc. d/b/a WestPlains Energy-Kansas, providing for interconnection of the Gray County Wind Project to the electric transmission system of MKEC at the Haggard Substation, the (“Gray County Wind Interconnection Agreement”);
WHEREAS, Ensign Wind is party to that certain Generator Interconnection Agreement dated April 22, 2011, by and among itself, Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (“SPP”), and MKEC, as subsequently amended, (“Ensign Wind Interconnection Agreement”) for interconnection of the Ensign Wind Project at the 115 kV Switching Station (also referred to as the Crooked Creek switchyard) on MKEC’s transmission system (“Ensign Permanent Point of Interconnection”);
WHEREAS, in 2012 SPP notified Ensign Wind that the injections of the Ensign Wind Project at the Ensign Permanent Point of Interconnection would be limited until all network upgrades required under the Ensign Wind Interconnection Agreement are constructed and in service; WHEREAS, Ensign Wind wishes to disconnect from the Ensign Permanent Point of Interconnection and instead connect on a temporary basis at MKEC’s 115 kV Haggard Substation (“Ensign Temporary Point of Interconnection”), which entails using Gray County Wind’s interconnection facilities (“Shared Facilities”), and Gray County Wind intends to allow Ensign Wind to share use of these Shared Facilities, which are described in Exhibit A attached hereto until Ensign Wind resumes use of the Ensign Permanent Point of Interconnection; WHEREAS, the Ensign Wind Interconnection Agreement is being amended (“Ensign Interconnection Agreement Amendment”) to reflect Ensign Wind’s use of the Temporary Point of Interconnection, and such amendment will establish certain operating restrictions for the Gray County Wind Project and the Ensign Wind Project while Ensign Wind uses the Temporary Point of Interconnection; and WHEREAS, Gray County Wind intends to grant Ensign Wind the right to utilize the Shared Facilities on the terms and conditions set forth herein, and the Parties wish to address other issues related to operation of the Gray County Wind Project and the Ensign Wind Project. NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the premises and of the mutual covenants and agreements contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is hereby acknowledged, the Parties hereby agree as follows: AGREEMENT 1. TERM; EARLY TERMINATION 1.1 Term and Termination: The term of this Agreement shall commence on the Effective Date and shall continue in effect until terminated (a) by mutual agreement of the Parties or, (b), without further action by either Party, upon the date that Ensign Wind Project ceases use of the Temporary Point of Interconnection due to resuming use of the Permanent Point of Interconnection. 2. GRANT OF SHARED FACILITIES RIGHTS 2.1 Grant: Gray County Wind hereby grants to Ensign Wind, during the term of this Agreement, and on the terms and subject to the conditions hereof, the non-exclusive right to access and utilize the Shared Facilities as may be reasonably necessary in connection with Ensign Wind’s ownership, operation and maintenance of the Ensign Wind Project. 2.2 Essential Nature: Gray County Wind hereby acknowledges that Ensign Wind’s rights to utilize the Shared Facilities are essential to the production of electric energy by the Ensign Project and the delivery of such energy to and through the Temporary Point of Interconnection to reach the electric transmission system of MKEC. 2.3 Vesting: The right to access and utilize the Shared Facilities granted to Ensign Wind hereunder shall vest in Ensign Wind as a contracting party hereunder without any transfer of title or leasehold interest in the Shared Facilities. 2.4 Costs and Expenses: In consideration of the right to access and utilize the Shared Facilities, Ensign Wind agrees to pay to Gray County Wind from time to time upon written demand by Gray County Wind its respective share of the costs and expenses set forth in Section 4.1 relating to the Shared Facilities utilized by Ensign Wind. For the avoidance of doubt, Ensign Wind is not obligated to pay or reimburse any such costs or expenses to Gray County Wind until such time, if any, as Ensign Wind shall have commenced use of such Shared Facilities.
3. NATURE OF SHARED FACILITIES RIGHTS
3.1 Limitation on Grant: Subject to Section 3.3, Gray County Wind grants the rights to Ensign Wind under this Agreement, to the extent that such rights do not limit in any material respect the ability of Gray County Wind to perform its obligations under any agreement, as the same may be hereafter modified or amended, that Gray County Wind has entered into, or enters into after the date hereof. 3.2 Interference: In no event shall either Party be entitled to exercise its rights to access and utilize the Shared Facilities if the exercise of such rights would materially interfere with or limit the reasonable and necessary access and utilization of the Shared Facilities by the other Party. Each Party agrees not to interfere with the reasonable and necessary utilization of the Shared Facilities by the other Party as permitted hereunder.
3.3 Prior Written Consent: Gray County Wind shall not take any action that results in the forbearance, foreclosure, termination or alteration of Ensign Wind’s access to, utilization of, or reliance upon the Shared Facilities without the prior written consent of Ensign Wind. 4. MAINTENANCE OF SHARED FACILITIES 4.1 Allocation of Certain Costs and Expenses: Gray County Wind shall be responsible for the costs and expenses of ownership or possession, operation, inspection, maintenance, repair, alteration, relocation, improvement and replacement of the Shared Facilities; provided, however, that Gray County Wind and Ensign Wind hereby agree that the costs and expenses of the operation, inspection, maintenance, repair, alteration, relocation, improvement and replacement of any Shared Facilities utilized by Ensign Wind shall be allocated among Gray County Wind and Ensign Wind equally from such time as Ensign Wind has commenced use of the Shared Facilities. 5. CHANGE IN OWNERSHIP; CHANGE IN LAW 5.1 Change in Common Beneficial Ownership: In the event that the membership interests of Gray County Wind and Ensign Wind are not at least 50% beneficially owned by the same direct or indirect parent entity, the Parties agree to use good faith efforts to negotiate (a) and implement a mutually acceptable ownership structure of the Shared Facilities that provides for the common ownership of the Shared Facilities by Gray County Wind and Ensign Wind and (b) mutually agreeable terms and execute a mutually agreeable agreement (or amendment to this Agreement) that recognizes such common ownership of the Shared Facilities. If the Parties are unable to reach such agreement on the terms and conditions that would replace or amend this Agreement, then the Party providing services on the Shared Facilities shall file an unexecuted agreement with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission pursuant to Section 205 of the Federal Power Act or its successor, and each Party reserves all rights under the Federal Power Act or its successor. 5.2 Change in Law: In the event that a change in the ownership of Gray County Wind and/or Ensign Wind or a change in the laws or regulations applicable to the Gray County Project, the Ensign Project or this Agreement requires the amendment, modification or replacement of this Agreement in order to satisfy any applicable federal, state or local regulatory requirements, the Parties agree to use good faith efforts to negotiate and implement mutually agreeable terms to accomplish such amendment, modification or replacement. If the Parties are unable to reach such agreement on the terms and conditions that would replace or amend this Agreement, then the Party providing services on the Shared Facilities shall file an unexecuted agreement with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission pursuant to Section 205 of the Federal Power Act or its successor, and each Party reserves all rights under the Federal Power Act or its successor. 6. CERTAIN COVENANTS 6.1 Condition Precedent to Use of Shared Facilities by Ensign Wind: Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, Ensign Wind agrees that it shall make no use of the Shared Facilities to transmit electrical energy to the electric transmission system of MKEC during such time, if any, as the Ensign Project is not party to an interconnection agreement with MKEC providing for the interconnection of the Ensign Project to the electrical transmission system of MKEC (as the same may be amended from time to time).
6.2 Operating Restrictions and Control of Output of Gray County Wind Project by Ensign Wind: (a) As specified in the Ensign Interconnection Agreement Amendment, injections of energy by the Gray County Wind Project and the Ensign Project, while the Ensign Project is interconnected at the Ensign Temporary Point of Interconnection, must be limited to 88 MVA (“Limited Operation”), unless otherwise agreed to by all the parties to the Ensign Interconnection Agreement. Notwithstanding anything else in this Agreement, to ensure that the combined output of the Gray County Wind Project and the Ensign Wind Project do not exceed 88 MVA, Gray County Wind hereby agrees to provide Ensign Wind with all authority and operational control over the Gray County Wind Project needed to ensure the combined output of the Gray County Wind Project and the Ensign Project (that is, the combined injection into the transmission system of MKEC at the Haggard Substation) does not exceed 88 MVA. This authority and control by Ensign Wind over the combined output of the Gray County Wind Project and the Ensign Wind Project will terminate when Ensign Wind ceases to use the Ensign Temporary Point of Interconnection. (b) Notwithstanding the role and authority of Ensign to ensure the combined output of the Gray County Wind Project and the Ensign Wind Project do not exceed 88 MVA, the Parties agree that Gray County shall have the responsibility of determining how the output of the Gray County Wind Project and the Ensign Wind Project is allocated to the various power sales agreements to which Gray County and Ensign, respectively, are parties. 6.3 Observance by Gray County Wind of Gray County Interconnection Agreement: During the term of this Agreement, Gray County Wind agrees to: (a) Operate the Gray County Project in compliance with the Gray County Interconnection Agreement; (b) Not take any action that would result in a breach by Gray County of the Gray County Interconnection Agreement. 6.4 Observance by Ensign Wind of Ensign Interconnection Agreement: During the term of this Agreement, Ensign Wind agrees to: (a) Operate the Ensign Project in compliance with the Ensign Interconnection Agreement; and (b) Not take any action which would result in a breach by Ensign Wind of the Ensign Interconnection Agreement. 7. MATERIAL BREACH 7.1 Material Breach by Ensign Wind. In the event of any material breach of this Agreement by Ensign Wind and Ensign Wind’s failure to cure such breach within a reasonable time not to exceed thirty (30) days after receipt of written notice from Gray County Wind describing such breach, Gray County Wind shall have the right, in addition to all remedies available to Gray County Wind at law or in equity, to (i) cure the breach on behalf of Ensign Wind, (ii) suspend Ensign Wind’s access to any or all of the Shared Facilities for so long as such default shall be continuing and remain uncured, or (iii) terminate this Agreement; provided, however, that in the event of any breach that may give rise to a default by Gray County Wind pursuant to the Gray County Interconnection Agreement, and Gray County Wind must respond immediately, then Gray County Wind shall not be required to provide Ensign Wind with notice and/or an opportunity to cure in order to exercise the remedy specified in clause (i) or (ii) of this sentence only. 7.2 Material Breach by Gray County Wind. In the event of any material breach of this Agreement by Gray County Wind and Gray County Wind’s failure to cure such breach within a reasonable time not to exceed thirty (30) days after receipt of written notice from Ensign Wind describing such breach, Ensign Wind shall have the right, in addition to all remedies available to Ensign Wind at law or in equity, to (i) cure the breach on behalf of Gray County Wind, or (ii) terminate this Agreement; provided, however, that in the event of any breach that may give rise to any default by Ensign Wind pursuant to the Ensign Interconnection Agreement, Ensign Wind shall not be required to provide Gray County Wind with notice and/or an opportunity to cure in order to exercise the remedy specified in clause (i) of this sentence only; and provided, further, that the remedy specified in clause (i) may be exercised, without prejudice to any right or remedy of Ensign Wind hereunder, by any lender of Ensign Wind. If Ensign Wind (or any lender thereof) chooses to cure any such breach on behalf of Gray County Wind, Gray County Wind shall reimburse Ensign Wind (or such lender) upon demand for all commercially reasonable costs incurred by Ensign Wind in curing such breach. 8. FORCE MAJEURE 8.1 Force Majeure. In the event of an act of God, government order or restraint, war (declared or undeclared) or warlike conditions, act of terrorism, blockade, revolution, strike, lockout, civil commotion, fire, flood, storm, epidemic or any other occurrence beyond a Party’s reasonable control (each a “Force Majeure Event”), such Party shall promptly notify the other Party thereof and, so long as such condition shall persist, such Party shall not be liable for the delay in performance of, or the failure to perform, its obligations (other than obligations for payment of amounts due hereunder) under this Agreement caused directly or indirectly thereby. The claiming Party shall give the other Party notice describing the particulars of the Force Majeure Event. Within fifteen (15) days after giving notice of the Force Majeure Event, the claiming Party shall give the other Party an estimate of the Force Majeure Event’s expected duration and probable impact. The claiming Party shall continue to furnish the other Party with timely regular reports during the continuation of the Force Majeure Event. Each Party shall immediately exercise commercially reasonable efforts to mitigate or limit the impact to its obligations hereunder as a result of the Force Majeure Event. 9. MISCELLANEOUS 9.1 Agreement to Cooperate. Each Party agrees to reasonably cooperate with the other Party so that, subject to the terms of this Agreement, each of the Gray County Project and the Ensign Project benefits from the full utilization and enjoyment of the Shared Facilities as is necessary for the efficient operation of each such wind energy project, subject to compliance with the Limited Operation requirements. 9.2 Relationship of Parties. The Parties do not intend to create hereby any joint venture, partnership, association or any other entity for the conduct of any business and nothing herein shall be deemed to authorize either Party to act on behalf of the other Party, except as specifically addressed herein. 9.3 Modification and Amendment. The terms of this Agreement may only be modified or amended in a writing signed by all of the Parties. 9.4 Waiver. The failure of a Party to insist upon or enforce strict performance of any of the provisions of this Agreement or to exercise any rights or remedies under this Agreement shall not be construed as a waiver or relinquishment to any extent of such Party’s right to assert or rely upon any such provisions, rights, and remedies in that or any other instance; rather, the same shall be and remain in full force and effect. 9.5 Enforceability. Any provision of this Agreement which is prohibited or unenforceable in any jurisdiction shall, as to such jurisdiction, be ineffective only to the extent of such prohibition, but shall be effective to the extent of such remaining provisions hereof. 9.6 Transfer of Shared Facilities. Except as set forth in Section 9.7, Gray County Wind may not transfer, sell, assign or sub-lease its ownership interest in the Shared Facilities or any portion thereof without the prior written consent of Ensign Wind. 9.7 Assignment. Neither Party may assign its rights or obligations hereunder without the prior written consent of the other Party, provided, however, that either Party may collaterally assign this Agreement to any entity, or such entity’s agent, in connection with a financing or a refinancing that that is directly or indirectly secured in whole or in part by the Gray County Project or the Ensign Project, as applicable. 9.8 Indemnification. Each Party shall indemnify, defend and hold the other Party harmless from any and all damages, losses, claims, including claims and actions relating to injury to or death of any person or damage to property, demand, suits, recoveries, costs and expenses, court costs, attorney fees, and all other obligations by or to third parties, arising out of or resulting from the indemnifying Party’s performance, or non-performance of its obligations under this Agreement, except in cases of gross negligence or intentional wrongdoing, by the indemnified party. However, in no event shall either Party be liable under any provision of this Agreement for any losses, damages, costs or expenses for any special, indirect, incidental, consequential, or punitive damages, including but not limited to loss of profit or revenue, loss of the use of equipment, cost of capital, cost of temporary equipment or services, whether based in whole or in part in contract, in tort, including negligence, strict liability, or any other theory of liability; provided, however, that damages for which a Party may be liable to the other Party under another agreement will not be considered to be special, indirect, incidental, or consequential damages hereunder. 9.10 Governing Law. This Agreement shall be governed by and constructed in accordance with the laws of the State of Kansas, without regard to its conflict of laws provisions. 9.11 Inspection of Records. Each Party shall have access to any records concerning the Shared Facilities held by the other Party upon reasonable notice and at reasonable times. 9.12 Section Headings. The section headings in this Agreement are for convenience of reference only and shall not modify, define, expand, or limit any of the terms or provisions hereof. 9.13 Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in one or more counterparts, each of which when so executed shall be deemed an original, and all of which when taken together shall constitute one and the same instrument.
[SIGNATURES APPEAR ON FOLLOWING PAGE] IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have caused this Shared Facilities Agreement to be executed as of the date first written above.
GRAY COUNTY WIND CENTER, LLC
By: ____________________________ Name: Charles S. Schultz Title: Secretary
ENSIGN WIND, LLC
By: ____________________________ Name: Charles S. Schultz Title: Secretary
EXHIBIT A SHARED FACILITIES
The “Shared Facilities” shall consist of the following: A section of the 115 kV bus, coupling capacitor voltage transformer, the steel dead-end tower and the revenue meters with its associated current transformer, potential transformer and communication devices on the customer side of the Point-of-Interconnection/Point-of-Change of Ownership switch at the Haggard 115 kV Switching station.
